ChatGPT said:
âœ… Fantastic question â€” and you nailed the comparison most people miss.
The condition: block in YARA-L is conceptually similar to a return statement in Python â€” itâ€™s the final logic that decides whether the rule triggers (true) or does nothing (false).
Letâ€™s unpack this carefully so you really understand what condition: does, why $process appears there, and how it works under the hood.

ðŸ§© 1. Rule Structure Reminder
Every YARA-L rule looks like this:
rule Rule_Name {
  meta:
    description = "What this rule detects"

  events:
    $process.metadata.event_type = "PROCESS_LAUNCH"

  condition:
    $process
}
Chronicle reads your rule top to bottom:
meta: â†’ just documentation (no logic).
events: â†’ defines the data pattern(s) to look for (variables and filters).
condition: â†’ evaluates if the rule should trigger (true/false).
ðŸ§  2. So What Does condition: Really Do?
Think of it like the â€œreturn expressionâ€ of your rule.
In Python, you might write:

def suspicious_process(event):
    if event["process_name"] == "powershell.exe":
        return True
    return False
In YARA-L, that same logic looks like:
rule Suspicious_Process {
  events:
    $process.metadata.event_type = "PROCESS_LAUNCH"
    $process.target.process.name = "powershell.exe"

  condition:
    $process
}
ðŸŸ¢ Here condition: $process means:
â€œIf any event matches the filters I defined for $process, trigger the rule (return true).â€
So yes â€” you can think of it as:
return $process
âš™ï¸ 3. When condition: Gets More Complex
You can use condition: to:
Combine multiple events ($process, $login, $network)
Use counts
Apply time windows
Add logical operators (and, or, not)
For example:
condition:
  $login.principal.user = $process.principal.user
  and $process.target.process.name = "powershell.exe"
  within 10m
That means:
â€œReturn true if both $login and $process matched, and they occurred within 10 minutes.â€
ðŸ§© 4. You Can Think of Each $variable as a Filtered Dataset
When you write:
$process.metadata.event_type = "PROCESS_LAUNCH"
Youâ€™re saying:
â€œGive me all events where event_type = PROCESS_LAUNCH.â€
Then, inside condition::
$process
means:
â€œIf there is at least one $process event that matched â†’ return true.â€
ðŸ’¡ 5. Examples Side-by-Side (YARA-L vs Python)
Concept	YARA-L	Python Equivalent
Define filter	$process.metadata.event_type = "PROCESS_LAUNCH"	if event["event_type"] == "PROCESS_LAUNCH":
Add condition	condition: $process	return True
Combine events	$login.principal.user = $process.principal.user	if login["user"] == process["user"]:
Count check	count($login) > 5 within 10m	if len(logins_in_10m) > 5:
Logical AND/OR	and, or, not	same as Python
ðŸ§± 6. Real Example
rule Detect_PowerShell {
  meta:
    description = "Detects PowerShell executions by non-admin users"

  events:
    $process.metadata.event_type = "PROCESS_LAUNCH"
    $process.target.process.name = "powershell.exe"
    $process.principal.user != "Administrator"

  condition:
    $process
}
Chronicle logic (Python-style pseudocode):
if (
    event.event_type == "PROCESS_LAUNCH"
    and event.process_name == "powershell.exe"
    and event.user != "Administrator"
):
    return True  # condition met â†’ alert triggered
ðŸ§® 7. More Advanced Example
Detect PowerShell after login by same user within 10 minutes:
rule Login_then_PowerShell {
  meta:
    description = "Detect PowerShell execution shortly after login"

  events:
    $login.metadata.event_type = "LOGIN"
    $process.metadata.event_type = "PROCESS_LAUNCH"
    $process.target.process.name = "powershell.exe"

  condition:
    $login.principal.user = $process.principal.user
    within 10m
}
Equivalent Python-like logic:
for login in login_events:
    for process in process_events:
        if login.user == process.user and (process.time - login.time) <= 10m:
            return True
ðŸš€ 8. Quick Recap
YARA-L Part	Purpose	Analogy
events:	Define variables + filters	â€œCollect the data you want to checkâ€
condition:	Evaluate logic between events	â€œReturn True if criteria metâ€
$process	Variable name for an event type	Like a dataset or object
$process in condition	â€œIf at least one matchâ€	Like return True
